<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-02-25T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-02-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="502" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d502">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">811.24 Raw Materials/1522:
                                Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-02-25">February 25,
                                        1941</date>.<lb/>[Received February 25—2:08 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>719. Department’s 537, February 19.<note n="47" xml:id="d502fn47">Not
                                    printed.</note> Following message from Sir John Hay for Mr.
                                Jesse Jones: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                    <p>“The decision to permit exports to continue at 100 per centum
                                        for the second quarter should ensure very adequate and rapid
                                        supplies of rubber for all American requirements. In view of
                                        reports still forthcoming of shortage of shipping for
                                        supplies already available at Eastern ports, wish to
                                        emphasize the importance of all steps being taken on your
                                        side to ensure without doubt that shipping will be fully
                                        adequate for the prompt transport of all rubber exports for
                                        America. Have informed Viles that Committee now decided to
                                        accept offer contained in your letter to me 5th November to
                                        purchase further 100,000 tons.”</p>
                                </quote>
                            </p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>